{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938011401/0735.xml":{"full_text":"WASHINGTON FORECAST\nBnow late this afternoon and tonight,\nlowest temperature about 28; Saturday\nfair, slightly colder. (Details on Page 11).\nNo. 17,627\nRoosevelt Plans to Smash Holding Companies\nPREMIER POST\nTURNED DOWN\nBY DALADIER\nNew Cabinet Plans\nI\nGiven Setback\nPARIS. Jan. 14 (I.N.S.).\u2014Ef\nforts to form a new cabinet re\nceived a fresh setback late to-\nday when Edouard Daiadier,\nradical Socialist ex-premier,\nflatly turned down the task.\nAlbert Sarraut, another radi\ncal socialist and minister with\nout portfolio in the last cabi\nnet, was then summoned before\nPresident Lebrun.\nI\nLONDON, Jan. 14 (1.N.5.).\nAmid excited dealings in French\nfrancs on the London foreign\nexchange market, Britain\u2019s ex\nchange equalization fund inter\nvened today and firmly pre\nvented wild speculative bids. As\nresult, the opening rate for\nthe franc was 154 to the pound\nsterling. This speedily became\nfirmer at 15 m in spot dealings.\nBy KENNETH T. DOWNS 1\nPARIS, Jan. 14 (I.N.S.)Com- 1\nmunist leaders demanded rein-\nstatement of a so-called \u201cpopular\nfront\u201d government in France to\nday as President Lebrun sought a\nsuccessor to Camille Chautemps,\nwhose cabinet resigned in a grave\npolitical and financial emergency.\nThroughout a long day of con\nferences, Leon Blum remained the\ndominant figure in deliberations 1\nbut not as a likelihood for the\npremiership.\nIn a half hour\u2019s conversation\nwith Lebrun, it was believed the\nPresident asked Blum to partici\npate in a new radical Socialist cabi\nnet, with Sarraut or Edouard Daia\ndier as premier. Such a cabinet\nwould have much the same char-\nacter as the Chautemps \u201cpopular\nfront\u201d government.\nPROPOSE CAUCUS\nBlum then talked with Marx\nDormoy, erstwhile minister of the\ninterior, and Vincent Auriol, for-\nmer minister of justice, over ad- 1\nvisability of convoking an extraor-\ndinary Socialist caucus tomorrow\nto debate Socialist participation in\nthe government.\nFollowing regular procedure, Le\nbrun first asked Chautemps to\nform a new ministry, but the latter\ndeclined.\nLebrun then turned to Edouard\nHerriot, veteran radical Socialist\nleader, hoping his acceptance\nmight solve the crisis. But Her- j\nriot also refused on the grounds\nthe factors of unrest which forced\nChautemps\u2019 resignation had not\nyet been removed.\nSARRAUT FAVORED\nAlbert Sarraut, a radical social\nist, minister of state in the Chau\ntemps cabinet, was favored as the\nnext choice. It was believed he\nmight be able to form a radical so\ncialist ministry similar to the gov\nernment he headed for a brief\nperiod prior to the \u201cpopular\nfront\u2019s\u201d uise to power.\nShould Sarraut be called on,\nprognosticators said, he might\nform a ministry with Vyon Delbos\nremaining as foreign minister, and\nGeorges Bonnet as finance min\nister with a \"free franc.\u201d\nWoman on Court\n0. K. to President\n(INS.) President Roosevelt to\nday declared he saw no reason\nwhy a woman should not sit on\nthe Supreme Court. The state\nment was made in response to a\nquestion put by a woman reporter\nas follows:\n\u201cEntirely apart from the exist\ning vacancy on the Supreme\nCourt, and without regard to\nany personality, do you see any\nreason why a woman should\nnot sit on the Supreme Court?\u201d\nEntered Second Claw Matter at\nPoet Office at Washington, D. C.\nHome Rule\nHere Asked\nIn House\nProviding for local suffrage, a\njoint resolution was introduced in\nthe House today proposing an\namendment to the Constitution to\nrelieve Congress of the duty of\noperating the Government of the\nDistrict of Columbia.\nThe resolution was introduced\nby Representative Jennings Ran\ndolph (D.) of West Virginia, a\nmember of the House District\nCommittee, who called attention to\nthe recent discussions in the Sen\nate as to local conditions and the\n\u201cburden\u201d placed on Congress for\noperating a municipal administra\ntion here.\nCALLS IT UNJUST\nDescribing the congressional bur\nden as \u201cunnecessary and unjust,\u201d\nMr. Randolph told Congress:\n\u201cThe problems of national\ngovernment have become so com\nplex and so strenuous that I am\nsure I speak for all my col\nleagues in saying none of us ever\nhas enough time to do his work\nas he would like to.\u201d\nONLY A VILLAGE\nMr. Randolph pointed out when\nthe Constitution was framed, giv\ning Congress exclusive legislative\npower over the District of Colum\nbia, the city was \u201cno more than a\nvillage and a vision.\u201d\n\u201cNobody conceived,\u201d he said,\n\u201cthe present rising and magnifi\ncent city of 625,000, nor the\nWashington we will have 10\nyears from now.\u201d\nSAFETY CHIEF\nSPEEDS, FINED\nIt can, and sometimes does, hap\npen to the best of us.\nHarry S. Wender, an attorney\nand chairman of the safety com\nmittee of the Federation of Citi\nzens Associations of the District,\nwas convicted on a charge of\nspeeding in Traffic Court today.\nWender appeared both as de\nfendant and counsel for the ac\ncused, but was sentenced to pay\na $5 fine by Judge Edward M.\nCurran.\nOfficer A. D. Clark, who made\nthe arrest at Fourth Street and\nthe Mall Southwest last night, tes\ntified Wender said that he was on\nthe way to attend a special meet\ning of the Traffic Safety Council,\nat which Traffic Director W. A.\nVan Duzerwas to be present, when\narrested.\nMrs. Wender, who was a passen\nger in the car, told the court that\nher husband is a careful driver\nand he is frequently critical of\ncareless driving by other motorists.\nEntente to Join\nAnti-League Bloc\nBERLIN, Jan. 14 (1.N.5.).\nUnder the leadership of Foreign\nMinister Joseph Beck of Poland,\nan oppositional bloc may confront\nthe League of Nations at its\nmeeting next week. Diplomatic\nquarters today predicted that\nPoland, Austria, Hungary, Bul\ngaria and Yugoslavia would be\nthe main elements in such a front,\nthus bolstering the anti-league\ncountries headed by Germany,\nItaly and Japan.\nRussia Executes 8\nHeld in Sabotage\nMOSCOW, Jan. 14 (1.N.5.).\n1 Eight persons were executed in\n1 Kazakshtan today for counter\nrevolutionary activities and sabo\ntage.\nTREASURY CONDITION\n(1.N.5.) Treasury balance Jan\nuary 12, $2,961,357,479.61; inter\nnal revenue, $6,762,050.56; cus\ntoms receipts, $9,189,068.50.\nssSjK OHbEI ME S\nSWIFT TRIAL\nPROMISED FOR\n2 D. C. BANDITS\nPolice to Release\nGirl Friend, 14\nSwift action was promised this\nafternoon in the punishment of\nthe two farmboy \u201cdrunken\nbandits\u201d who, with a 14-year-old\ngirl companion Wednesday night\nstaged eight District holdups.\nActing District Attorney David\nA. Pine is ready to rush the\ncharges before the Grand Jury,\nand, after probable swift indict\nment, to try the men as soon as a\ncourt can be found.\nThe girl will be sent home in\nthe care of her parents, police\nsaid this afternoon.\nCAPITAL AROUSED\nNo reign of terror in recent\nyears has so aroused the District\nas the crime debauch of the Tip\npett brothers, Ellis, 20, and Ells\nworth 17, in which the older boy,\nso drunk he staggered, waved his\ngun at six of his victims and took\ntwo shots at a seventh. Both\nyouths and Margaret Rose O\u2019Brien,\nthe girl, are natives of Ardmore,\nMd.\nSenators and Congresmen have\nmade the case the sugject of\nheated comment on the Hill; so\ncial agencies have issued Masts\nagainst existing conditions in the\nDistrict, which they say fosters\nsuch criminality, and citizens asso\nciations have made bitter protests,\ndemanding greater protection.\nCAUGHT AT INN\nBut all agree the Metropolitan\npolice are to be commended for\ntheir capture of the trio at Wood\nbridge Inn, where they rested from\ntheir robbery orgy to play cards\nand sober up.\nThe tip which resulted in the\narrest came from Samuel I. Dur\nphy, proprietor of the inn, who\nrecognized the youths from news\npaper descriptions- He will be\npaid the $25 reward, police said.\nFor two hours this morning both\nyouths were grilled at Police\nHeadquarters and then taken,\none to the Fifth precinct and the\nother to the Ninth precinct, to\nawait a police \u201clineup\u201d tonight\nbefore police prefer charges.\nPEAKE WINS PRAISE\nDistrict Attorney Pine issued\ninstructions that immediately fol\nlowing the preliminary hearing,\nhis office be notified. He said he\nwould immediately bring the case\nto a Grand Jury,, and thereafter\nseek the earliest possible trial of\nthe Tippetts.\nSpeeding to Woodbridge, police\nsurrounded the inn. Elsworth Tip\npett was coming downstairs as\nthey entered. He was seized and\nhandcuffed.\nDetectives found Ellis and Miss\nO\u2019Brien seated in their room.\nHanging on the wall were two\nlumberjackets, each containing\nloaded pistols.\nWhen arrested, the pair had\nabout S4O.\n(Other Details On Page 3)\nJustice Cardozo\n\u201cHolding Gains\u2019\u2019\n(1.N.5.). Justice Cardozo, of\nthe Supreme Court, who is\nsuffering from heart trouble,\nagain held his own during the\nnight. Dr. J. P. Earnest repoprted\ntoday.\n\u201cJustice Cardozo has held the\nimprovement which he showed\nyesterday morning,\u201d said the\nphysician\u2019s bulletin. \u201cThe doc\ntors find this a hopeful sign.\u201d\n\u2018\u2022Give Me Back My Toy*!\u201d Cried\nthe Nobleman. An English Earl Tire*\nof Hl* Manikin Playmate, Turni Her\nOut and Sues Her for the Tin Soldiers,\nPicture Books and Little Trains With\nWhich They Played Together. An Un\nusual Illustrated Feature Article in\nThe American Weekly, With Sunday's\nWashington Herald-Times.\nCaptured--in Pajamas\n1 f!| HL\nI I\nI I\nI f\n1 I I\n\nH M i I 9.\n-A \u25a0if\n_ j\nWashington Times Photo by Jackie Martin\nPICTURED IN pajamas in the Women\u2019s Bureau here is\nMargaret Rose O\u2019Brien, 14-year-old girl of Ardmore, Md.,\nwho was seized when officers arrested two youths from the\nsame town in a Virginia tavern\u2014on suspicion that the boys,\nEllis and Ellsworth Tippett, were the intoxicated thugs who\nstaged a series of seven holdups here Wednesday.\nblasts\nDodd Free to Criticize\nNazis, Hull Tells Envoy\n(1.N.5.) The Hitler govern-.:\nment, through its ambassador, Dr.i:\nHans Dieckhoff, today presented\na vigorous verbal protest to the\nUnited States over the criticism\nof Germany made by former Am- 1\nbassador William E. Dodd in New\nYork last night\u2014but was firmly\nreminded by Secretary of State\nCordell Hull that the United\nStates is a country of free speech.\nDieckhoff pointed out that\nsuch statements as Dodd, who\nrecently resigned as the Ameri\ncan ambassador to Germany,\nFRIDAY, JANUARY 14, 1938\n\u25bamade at a dinner in his honor in\nNew York, arouses resentment in\nGermany and is inimical to good\nrelations between Germany and\nthe United States.\nThe U. S. Government, Hull em\nphasized, does not have control\nover the utterances of the former\nambassador, or any other private\ncitizen.\nU. S. FOOD SALES\nCHICAGO, Jan. 14 (INK).\u2014In\n1937, food sales in the United\nStates will total $10,692,400,000,\naccording to Clarence Francis,\npresident of General Foods Cor\nporation.\nControl by Minority\nCited to Back Drive\nCapital \u201cWater\u201d'\nScored By\nPresident\n(INK). Determined to elimi\nnate the power in the \u201cfour-inch\ntail,\u201d President Roosevelt today\ndeclared that his administration\nwas leading up to an elimination\nof holding companies entirely\u2014\nnot only in the utilities field, but\nin other industries.\nThe President said he had no\nobjection to investment trusts so\nlong as they did not vote stock at\na board meeting. He made it clear,\nhowever, that his administration\nwas determined to get what he\ncalled \u201cthe wind and the water\u201d\nout of the capital structure of the\ncountry\u2019s business.\nUNCERTAIN OF PROCEDURE\nMr. Roosevelt was asked whether\nhe would undertake this through\nlegislation or through an exercise\nof the taxing power, but he said\nhe did not know exactly how the\nproblem would be approached.\nHe was most emphatic in his\npress conference in condemning\nthe capital structure setup of the\npublic utilities wherein $13,000,-\n000,000 in investments is con\ntrolled by $600,000,000, Then the\nPresident was asked whether he\nwould eliminate holding com\npanies In other fields. He sajd\nthe same rule should apply.\nSpecifically, the President cited\nthe point of a bank which comes\nunder the domination of a big\ncentral bank. He asked the press\nconference why that bank could\nnot be allowed to run itself with\nGovernment supervision.\nCITES WILLKIE DATA\nThe President\u2019s discussion of\nholding companies developed\nfrom questions about a memoran\ndum left him on November 23 by\nWendell Willkie, head of Com\nmonwealth Southern. He read\nthe highlights of the memoran- j\ndum.\nOn Willkie\u2019s proposal that utility\nvaluation be established by court\nrule as of a given date and\nthereafter under the \u201ctruth-in\ninvestment\u201d principle, the Presi\ndent emphatically said he thought\nit was wrong for the Government\nto admit a crime had been com\nmitted and still leave the water\nand wind in the capital structure.\nWillkie\u2019s proposal for modifica\ntion of the so-called death-sentence\nclause was referred to by the\nPresident as another instance of\nthe \u201c4-inch tail trying to wag the\n96-inch dog.\u201d\nWillkie objected to Federal loans\nand grants to municipalities for\nconstruction of power plants. The\nPresident pointed out that the\nmunicipality was entitled to do as\nit pleased in such matters and\nthat this was not a matter of\nGovernment jurisdiction.\nDOUBTS OPERATING HARM\nAsked if such grants were not\na direct Federal subsidy, the 1\nPresident said he saw little differ-\nence between that and the subsidy\nany given district would get in the\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 1)\nI\nSnow Due Today;\nFair Tomorrow\nWashington is in for a snow\nstorm this afternoon and tonight,\naccording to the forecast of the\nUnited States Weather Bureau.\nThe official forecast reads: \u201cSnow\nlate this afternoon and tonight.\nLowest temperature tonight about\n28. Saturday fair and slightly\ncolder.\u201d The lowest temperature\novernight was 27 degrees at 6\na. m. Yesterday\u2019s low was 35 at\n8 a. m. and the high was 39 at\n3:50 p. m.\nHOME\nE DITIOfM\nWhite House, Capitol Act\nIn Battle on Recession\nThe White House and the Capitol were the focal\npoints today in the battle to bring the nation out of\nthe business recession.\nHighlights were:\n1 President Roosevelt, at his press conference, declared\nthe Administration was leading the way toward tak\ning \u201cthe wind and water\u201d out of the capital structures of\nthe Nation\u2019s industries. He let it be known the Adminis\ntration is bent upon wiping out holding companies from\nthe utilities as well as other industries.\n2 J. D. A. Morrow, Pennsylvania industrialist and presi-\ndent of the Pittsburgh Coal Company, testifying be\nfore the Senate Unemployment Committee, declared the\ncurrent business recession \u201cstarted right here in Washing\nton\u201d and will have \u201cto be cured right here in Washington.\u201d\n3 Representatives of capital, labor and one-time \u201cbrain-\ntrusters\u201d converged on the White House to offer\nrecommendations for terminating the business slump.\nMine Head Blames\nSlump on New Deal\nMorrow Demands Uncertainty Be Ended\nand Administration Be Frank\nBy ROBERT A. McGILL\n(1.N.5.) A blunt-spoken Pennsylvania industrialist declared\nbefore the Senate Unemployment Committee today that the cur\nrent business recession was \u201ccreated right here in Washington.\u201d\nLewis Called\nWith Trade\nI\nChiefs\nI\n(1.N.5.) A group comprising]\nrepresentatives of capital, labor\nand the erstwhile \"brain trust\" of\nthe New Deal converged upon the|\nWhite House today to put before]\nPresident Roosevelt some recom\nmendations for pulling the coun\ntry out of the business slump.\nTUGWELL ON HAND\nCapital was represented by such\nfigures as Thomas W. Lamont, a\npartner in the firm of J. P. Mor\ngan Co., and Owen D. Young,\nhead of the General Electric Com-;\npany. Labor was represented b>\nbushy-browed John L- Lewis, di\nrector general of the CIO, accom\npanied by his chief aide, Philip]\nMurray, CIO vice chairman.\nThe erstwhile brain trusters I\nwere Rexford G. Tugwell, A. A.\nBerle, and Charles Taussig, all of\nwhom were prominently identified\nwith the administration in its\nearlier days. They are now out\nside the Government, engaged in\nprivate business.\nThe members of this group have\nbeen engaged in private confer\nences for some time, it is under\nstood, although whether at Presi\ndent Roosevelt\u2019s instigation is not\ndefinitely known. The prevailing\nbelief was that Tugwell, Berle and\nTaussig initiated the parleys\nwhich have been held in New\nYork, with the knowledge of Mr.\nRoosevelt.\nLEWIS BID SURPRISES\nThe inclusion of John L. Lewis\nin the group, however, was some\nthing of a surprise. Hitherto, la\nbor leaders have not been in the\nvarious groups called to the White\nHouse. Lewis has not been to the\nWhite House in many months, and\nof late has been inclined to be ex-;\ntremely critical of Administration\nI policies. I\nTHREE CENTS\nHe was J. D. A. Morrow, presi\ndent if the Pittsburgh Coal Com\npany, and, while offering to \u201cco\noperate\u201d with the Government In\nrecovery measures, he called upon\nthe New Deal to clarify its policies\ntoward industry, and to \u201crectify\nits mistakes.\u201d\nUNCERTAINTY CITED\n\u201cThis present depression is a\nmatter of deep concern to the\nheads of every business and in\ndustrial enterprise, large and\nsmall,\u201d said Morrow. \"It was not\nof their making or seeking. It\ncame upon them because a\nspreading doubt and uncer\ntainty as to the future dried up\norders for the output of mills\nand mines and factories.\n\u201cOur company and 4 every\nother will give the Government\nevery assistance to restore pros\nperity. But this willingness on\nthe part of industry is not\nenough. The shoe is on the\nother foot. In our view this\ndepression was created here in\nWashington.\nDEMANDS FRANKNESS\n\u201cIt will have to be cured here\nin Washington by a frank\nacknowledgement of some mis\ntakes that have been made; by\na clear and unequivocal state\nment of future policies without\nany intimations or suspicions of\n(Continued on Page 2, CoL 4)\nINDEX\nPage\nAndrew R. Kelley 16\nBirths and Marriages 26\nBoake Carter 25\nClassified Ads 31, 32, 33\nComics 28, 29\nDrama 16, 17\nEditorials 12\nEvalyn Walsh McLean2s\nFlora Macdonald 22\nFrank \u201cBuck\" O\u2019Neill.3o\nHarry Costello 30\nHelen Essary 25\nInquiring Photographer ....12\nJ. Earle Moser 17\nKirk Miller 30\nPaul Mallon 13\nPeter Carter 22\nRadio 27\nWoman's Page 20","height":"25827","width":"20234"}}
